The paper presents a novel framework for multi-agent path finding (MAPF) that combines reinforcement and imitation learning to teach fully-decentralized policies. This work involves the use of machine learning techniques such as reinforcement learning and imitation learning, which are commonly associated with the cs.AI and cs.LG sub-categories. The application of these techniques is in the context of robotics and automation, which falls under the cs.RO sub-category. The paper also deals with the coordination of multiple agents, which is a key aspect of multi-agent systems and thus relevant to the cs.SY sub-category. Finally, the paper explicitly mentions "multi-agent learning" in the abstract, which suggests that it could also be relevant to the cs.MA sub-category.
